parameter 1: The UK cinema version was cut by 1 min 1 sec by the BBFC to remove scenes of a cockfight. The 1986 Rank video version was pre-edited by the distributors to remove most of the scene beforehand and subsequently the cuts were reduced to 14 secs. However MGM submitted the original cinema print for the 2003 DVD release and thus 49 secs were cut from the same scene.
parameter 2: The director's re-edited television version of the movie includes, among other things, an extra musical number for actress Eileen Brennan. Immediately following the scene between Brennan and Cybill Shepherd outside of the racetrack, Brennan sings "It Ain't Etiquette" (from Dubarry Was a Lady) to Shepherd.  Clues to this excised number can be found in a rather abrupt and obvious edit in the theatrical version.
parameter 3: TV version was re-edited and reworked by director Peter Bogdanovich and runs three minutes shorter than the theatrical release.
parameter 4: Released with separate English, French and German soundtracks.
parameter 5: Swedish cinema version had following songs deleted/shortened: "From Alpha to Omega" and "I love Him" was removed; "Which", "At Long Last Love", "Let's Misbehave" and "Just One of Those things" were shortened.

parameter 13: Mondo Macabro released two DVD versions: the R-rated cut is available only through Blockbuster and the Unrated cut is available through retailers. To add further confusion, the Unrated discs will sometimes proclaim them to be the "R-Rated Cut". The key difference between the versions: the R-rated disc has no extras, the Unrated disc is loaded with special features, like a documentary, two commentaries, trailers, and audition tapes.
